tel itself must be about the quitest we have been to in DXB as regards no noise around the rooms or hallways and doors that shut without banging.Overall it was a good stay and would think about going there again if we wanted a city hotel.At checkout we were asked how our stay was and when we pointed out the problems on the room issue the hotel manager came over and expressed deep concern that we had had a problem and took notes of what our complaints were and advised us to ask for him if we come back again to the hotel .My overall view of the hotel was of a very good hotel good for business clients as well as tourists and ideally situated for getting about,also with no building work around it to speak of it is always quiet and relaxing	
Jun 2 2008 	Take advantage of the pool at the Grand Hyatt	Stayed at the GH for 2 weeks on business trip. The hotel has a great entrance, and a very comfortable lobby where you can meet up with ppl and sit down for a chat. Although I was booked into a standard room, it was spacious, with a small walk-in closet, large LCD tv, writing desk, couch, etc. Service was efficient and friendly, room service was also good. Tried almost all the restaurants, and liked the Manhattan Grill the most. Awtar was fine for Lebanese food (although I prefer Al Nafoorah at Emirates Towers). Peppercrab was good too. Breakfast was not very inspiring, and only complaint is that my coffee always arrived towards the middle of my breakfast, despite repeated reminders at the entrance, before I sat down and after digging in to my breakfast. On the weekend I had room service breakfast, which was cheaper than the buffet (eggs and bacon, toast, coffee), and quite prompt.One thing you should not miss is the swimming pool, both outdoor (huge) and indoor, jacuzzi, steam sauna etc. I especially loved the cool damp face towels and iced water they provide in the changing room. Unfortunately I only had one weekend there, but I went down to the pool both days. The GH is located near Wafi City mall, just 10-15 min walk from the hotel. It was a pleasant walk in Feb, but recommend you take the taxi after March. The mall has a food court selling arabian food on the top floor, with many kebabs, salads, sweets etc. which was quite nice. There's also a Chinese restaurant in Wafi Pyramids (where all the restaurants are), but the one you should really try is Indian food - Asha. You may need to make reservations, but the mango lassi is to die for.	
