Apr 2 2007 	2nd time and every bit as good	My husband and I spent 8 days at the Grand Hyatt Dubai in March 2007. This is our second visit to GH Dubai and I'm happy to say that the hotel and rooms have been immaculately maintained, and everything is as perfect as we remember. We did consider staying at the newer Park Hyatt this time around, but after some deliberation and research, the Grand Hyatt it was. Other hotels we considered included the new Kempinski (connected to the Mall of the Emirates) and Grosvenor House - but the Grand Hyatt's location and memories of our last stay brought us back here. The hotel is excellently located - about 10 minutes by taxi to Deira City Center and Bur Juman Center, and around 25 minutes to the Mall of the Emirates. Festival City is about 15 minutes away too (a must if you want to visit IKEA and the largest Marks and Spencer store outside the UK). Expect to pay around Dhs 15 ($4) to City Center/Bur Juman and Dhs 40 ($11) to the Mall of the Emirates - if there's not too much traffic. We booked a Creekside King room and used our Gold Passport points to upgrade to a Club Creek View room (3000 points for a 4 night slab). The view is awesome and unobstructed, overlooking the pool and landscaped area and onto the creek. I spent most mornings perched on the carpet in front of the floor to ceiling windows, enjoying my coffee and the incredible view.A word of caution about the club rooms - the standard club room is 39 sq mts, while the club creek view rooms are 44 sq mts, I'm not sure what the exact difference is other than the space, but I would almost always shell out a little more for the club creek view. BMW 7 series transfers are provided for club rooms. On arrival at the hotel, we stepped out of the car and were instantly welcomed by a club floor executive who was expecting us, and he escorted us up to the club lounge for private check in. Complimentary continental breakfast is provided each morning - the usual croissants, muffins, danish, cereal etc and some Arabic selection too. More than adequate. Other Club floor extras are available - afternoon tea and cookies, evening cocktails etc - but we never really found the time to utilize any of this. The thing we loved is no matter what time of day, whether early in the morning or late at night, the hotel always seems to be full of people moving around but without being too noisy, and this gave it a lively and happening feel. Housekeeping is fairly discreet, we never really noticed when they did up the rooms, but everything was spic and span when we returned.The one thing the hotel did not provide was free high speed internet access - this would be been a nice touch, and it is something provided by some other comparable hotels in Dubai. I would also like to see large screen LCD or plasma televisions in the room. I would totally recommend this hotel to anyone visiting Dubai and looking for convenience and luxury combined. Note that prices differ depending on season, and the Dubai calender is full of events, exhibitons, festivals etc and all these affect room rates. So do some research.	
